0":"1495–1560","1514–1589":"1514–1589","1499–1566":"1499–1566","1500/10/15":"15 oktober 1500","1514":"1514","1589":"1589","1566":"1566","1499":"1499","9 May 1566":"9 mei 1566","1495":"1495","1560":"1560","Bradley,Kildwick Craven West Riding,,England":"Bradley, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beaumont, Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whitley Beaumont, Yorkshire, England":"Whitley, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yate Weston Pulton Sandhurst Morslade Ablyngton, Devon, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1499–9 May 1566":"1499–9 May 1566","1495–1560":"1495–1560","1514–1589":"1514–1589","1499–1566":"1499–1566","1500/10/15":"15 October 1500","1514":"1514","1589":"1589","1566":"1566","1499":"1499","9 May 1566":"9 May 1566","1495":"1495","1560":"1560","Bradley,Kildwick Craven West Riding,,England":"Bradley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Beaumont, Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Whitley Beaumont, Yorkshire, England":"Whitley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Yate Weston Pulton Sandhurst Morslade Ablyngton, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jane Beaumont was born in 1499, in Bradley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir John John Galmyngton Roger Boys John Beaumount Thomas de Wyllyngton William Brythlegh John Poulet Thomas de Wyllyngton John Beaumont on 15 October 1500, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 9 May 1566, in Whitley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1499–9 May 1566":"1499–9. mai 1566","1495–1560":"1495–1560","1514–1589":"1514–1589","1499–1566":"1499–1566","1500/10/15":"15. oktoober 1500","1514":"1514","1589":"1589","1566":"1566","1499":"1499","9 May 1566":"9. mai 1566","1495":"1495","1560":"1560","Bradley,Kildwick Craven West Riding,,England":"Bradley, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaumont, Yorkshire, , England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whitley Beaumont, Yorkshire, England":"Whitley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yate Weston Pulton Sandhurst Morslade Ablyngton, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1499–